Predicting the Chance of Winning in Valorant

Colin Nguyen, Christina Ngo

Introduction

Valorant is a popular first-person shooter game developed and published by Riot Games. It was released in 2020 and has quickly become a fan favorite for its fast-paced gameplay and strategic elements. In the game, players assume the role of agents, characters with unique abilities and weapons, who compete against each other in a variety of game modes. Valorant has gained a following for its intense and competitive nature, making it a popular choice for both casual and professional players. For more information can be found here.

Strategy, teamwork, and individual skill is highly valued in Valorant that can help win many games. Developing a good game plan and working well with your teammates can give you a significant advantage over the other team. There are much more factors that will dictate a win or loss in a match, which this tutorial will cover.

Our goal is to tidy the in-game data given to us and provide a valuable insight into which agents will affect your win percentages on games. Having a good understanding of the game and your own abilities, as well as those of your opponents, can help you make better decisions and improve your chances of victory. Lastly, knowing what gun to use and having good aim and being able to make quick, accurate shots can be crucial in winning gunfights and in clutching moments to defuse bombs.

For readers unfamiliar with this game, we hope this analysis will make you interested in trying out Valorant and provide some evidence on which agents are best to pick starting out as a new player. Additionally helping you choose which gun best to use to help increase your chances of winning. For experienced players, we hope to show interesting unknown statistics and maybe even give them new things to try when they play.

Grabbing Data

Getting Started
To start our project, we start by looking for data on Valorant and players. Riot Games does offer their API keys out to developers, but unfortunately, Riot was more strict with Valorant data in comparison to their other games. We were forced to look elsewhere and luckily, we were able to find a data on Kaggle that contains data of player's statistics in mostly Diamond 3 and above in Valorant in Act 3 Chapter 4 to make our data more usable.

Tidying up the Data

Using the unique() method, we were able to obtain the list of regions in the region column to check if all regions were set to NaN. While parsing the csv file, we noticed it was only North America and replaced all NaNs with NA to stand for "North America". Because we play on NA servers and to make the data easier to work with, all regions except for NA was dropped.The given data set has already grabbed data from the top ranks that includes Radiant to Immortal 1 so the data is much more accurate to lessen smurf accounts and other factors that could skew the data.

Exploring the Data

Getting to Know All The Agents

In Valorant, each player chooses a character known as an "Agent" to play as, each with their own unique abilities and role within the team. There are currently about 20 agents in Valorant however with our dataset only includes 19, since we were not able to get the latest dataset with the newest updates. Moving on, each with agents own unique abilities and playstyle. The 20 agents in Valorant are broadly classified into 4 big roles that will affect your playstyle and gameplay.

Duelists are agents that excel at one-on-one fights and can hold their own against multiple enemies. They often have abilities that allow them to sustain themselves in fights or deal high burst damage. They also create space for your team by entrying in for your team.

Initiators are agents that excel at starting fights and disrupting the enemy team's positioning. They often have abilities that allow them to close the distance quickly and get in close to engage the enemy. They provide information for your team in order to assist the team when charging into battle.

Sentinels are defensive agents that excel at controlling an area and protecting their team. They often have abilities that allow them to erect barriers or set up traps to control the battlefield. They can watch flanks, both on attack and defender rounds.

Controllers are agents that excel at disrupting the enemy team's positioning and denying areas of the map. They often have abilities that allow them to create obstacles or block off areas of the map.

Picking which agent is to play in a match is hard with all the possibilities, so we will create multiple bar graphs that would help show which agent is most popular for each role to help inexperienced players which agent they should pick. First we will make a new dataframe (grouping by agent and role), sum the number of agents been picked, wins, and calculate win ratios for each roles and popularity of each agents in every role, then show the relationships.

However, it doesn't mean that the agents is best in the current meta or in other words the best strategist to win games. So we will create a bar graph to show you which agents have the highest win percentage.

Total Games Played

We came to the realization that we only had the wins and each player's winning percentage, which would make it really hard to calculate data and analyze as we move forward. To calculate this, we divided the given win percentage of each user by 100. We used that number to divide wins to get total games that user had played in the Act.

In [17]:
#  creating a new column for total games
val_stats['total_games'] = val_stats['wins']/(val_stats['win_percent']/100)
In [18]:
# creating a list for total wins of each agent
total_wins = []
# looping through the agents
for agent in agents:
    all_agents = val_stats[val_stats['agent_1'] == agent]
    # summing up the wins for each agent
    total = all_agents['wins'].sum()
    total_wins.append(total)
# adding column into our dataframe
agent_top['Total of Wins'] = total_wins

Once we got the total amount of games played for each agent. We need to get the total amount of wins for each agent which the steps are shown below.

In [19]:
# creating a list for total games of each agent
total_games = []
# looping through the agents
for agent in agents:

    # summing up the games played for each agent

agent_top['Total of games'] = total_games
# creating a temp dataframe to reference the added columns for later use
final = pd.DataFrame
final = agent_top

Now that we have the total amount of wins for each agent and the total amount of games played for each agent. We can now find the win percentage of every agent by taking the amount of wins and dividing it by the amount of games played. Then we are able to graph the win percentages of every agent as a bar plot.

In [20]:
total_win_per = []
for agent in agents:
    all_agents = final[final['Agents'] == agent]
    # getting the win percentage by dividing the total wins by total games
    # multiply 100 because we want number to be a percentage
    total = 100*(float(all_agents['Total of Wins']/all_agents['Total of games']))
    total_win_per.append(total)
# adding column into our dataframe to create bargraph
agent_top['Win Percentage'] = total_win_per

Which Gun has the most kills

Moving on to which guns to use. Valorant is also a precise gunplay so we need to know which guns to use during our matches. We were provided with information from the players chosen primay used gun. We wanted to see which gun gets the most kills for each player on average. To do so, we iterated through each row and summed up totals based on the gun listed in the column "gun1_name". We divided the total by the number of users, who chose that specific gun.

temp = pd.DataFrame()

# iterating through the list of weapon choices
for weapon in weapons:

# inserting new found data into the new df
temp['weapon'] = weapons

Winning Percentage Based on Gun Choice

Moving on, we want to see if your primary gun choice will affect your win percentage and what gun is best to increase your chances of winning. In order to do so, we will calculate the win percentages based on the gun you use during a match. We will take the primary gun that players win with and divide that by the total amount of games the players have played to get the win percentage per gun.

win_gun = []

    if weapon == "Classic" or weapon == "Ghost":

Winning Percentage Based on Guns Analysis

Winning percentage Based on Ranks

Now, we want to compare the win percentages based on ranks to see if rank affect your win percentage. Keep in mind that the dataset is majority Radiants, Immortals, and Diamonds, so the data is a bit skewed since there are a few Silver and Golds.

To get our win percentage based on people's ranks, we will go through our dataframe and total up the wins for each rank. Then we will divide by the total amount of games that have been played. We will then multiple that number by 100 to get the actual percentage.

After getting the winning percentage of each rank, we will plot it as a bargraph to compare the winning percentage in each ranks.

In [34]:
# grabbing the unique list of all of the possible ratings in this dataset
ratings = val_stats.rating.unique()
In [35]:
# creating a list to store all of the winning percentage of each rank
rating = pd.DataFrame()
win_rating = []
rank = []

# iterating through each possible rank and grabbing the data pertaining to that rank
for rating in ratings:
    rank_data = val_stats[val_stats['rating']==rating]
    wins = rank_data['wins'].sum()
    total = rank_data['total_games'].sum()
    
    # calculating winning percentages based on ranks
    win_per = (wins/total)*100
    
    rank.append(str(rating))
    win_rating.append(win_per)
In [36]:
# graphing winning percentage v. rank
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

plt.title("Winning Percentage v. Rank")

plt.ylabel("Winning Percentage")
Out[36]:

Winning percentage Based on Ranks Analysis

As you can see in the bargraph above, each rank's winrate is about the same beside Gold 1 because of our dataset is skewed. Besides the rank of Gold 1, the other ranks win percentage is similar. This means that in each rank, your rank doesn't affect the amount of games you win because you will be playing against other people that have the same skill level as you.

Predicting Independent Variable that Influence Data

In this section, we want to see how your kill-death ratio will affect your chances you winning your matches. Theres a variety of predictions models we could use but given the amount of data given to us, we will solely focus on linear regression.

First, we are going to graph the kill-death ratio as the x axis and win percent as the y axis. We will then implement a line regression to predict how kill-death ratio can affect the chances of you winning.

In [37]:
# graphed winning percentages as we get higher k/d ratios
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.scatterplot(x="kd_ratio", y="win_percent", data=val_stats, hue='rating')

x = val_stats['kd_ratio']
y = val_stats['win_percent']

# graphing linear regression
m, b = np.polyfit(x,y,1)
plt.plot(x, m*x+b)
plt.ylim((0,105))
plt.title('Kill-To-Death Ratio v. wins')
plt.xlabel('Kill-To-Death Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Win percentage')
Out[37]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Win percentage')

Winning percentage Based on Kill-Death Ratio Analysis

As you can see in the graph above with the linear regression line. Higher your Kill to death ratio, the higher percentage you will win your games. This applies to all ranks of Valorant players as the ranks in the data shows their kill death ratio based on their win percentage.

Now in this last section, we will hypothesis to test if your headshot percentage rate affect your chances of winning. We will first graph a scatterplot with headshot percentage as the x value and win percentage as the y axis. Then we will implement a linear regression line to predict and see if your headshot percentage rate affect your win percentage.

Winning a game is more than hitting headshots, since Valorant is a tactical team game.
